‘ Of freed mortel and in deeds Yat yair don is; Tol, Tem, Soc, Sao, with yren and with water deme And yat the land, etc.'

The reference to ordeal by hot iron and by water takes us back to times long before the date of this chartei· in its present form. The English ordea] went out of use soon after the Norman Conquest. But it seems not unlikely that the iron, or one of the irons used at Ripon, was preserved as ‘Su Wilffid's buming-i1·on,' which will be noticed in connection with its occurrence in the Account-rolls as a source of income up to the Reformation.
